ed Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ogilvy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Scottish:  see  Ogilvie  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ogilvie","meanings":["Scottish: variant of   Oglesby  , a habitational name from the barony of Ogilvie in Glamis (Angus), whose name is probably Pictish, of uncertain origin and meaning.","Irish: adopted for   Gilboy  ."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Alexander Ogilvy was born in 1199, in Angus, Scotland, United Kingdom, his father, Gilbert Ogilvy, was 22 and his mother, Maud, was 34. He married Mrs. de Ogilvie before 1225, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 5 sons. He died in 1250, in Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 51, and was buried in Scotland."},"et":{"1199–1250":"1199–1250","1197–Male":"1197–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1225–1305":"1225–1305","1235–1335":"1235–1335","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1265–Male":"1265–Surnud","1266–Male":"1266–Surnud","1177–Male":"1177–Surnud","1165–Female":"1165–Surnud","before 1225":"enne 1225","1165":"1165","1197":"1197","1240":"1240","1250":"1250","1305":"1305","1225":"1225","1335":"1335","1235":"1235","1266":"1266","1199":"1199","1177":"1177","1265":"1265"